# Running the Customer Milk Purchase Simulation

## Problem Addressed
The code deals with the issue of maximizing customer experience at a store where patrons interact with cashiers and refrigerators. The main objective is to reduce the amount of lost business by strategically allocating patrons to refrigerators. The system is meant to mimic real-world situations in which different customers may have different needs for milk and refrigerators may need to be restocked.

## Methodology 
This simulation uses Q-learning, a reinforcement learning technique, as its methodology. By monitoring the system's current state—queue lengths at refrigerators—the Q-learning agent learns how to make choices that will maximize long-term benefits. After every activity, the rewards are used to update the Q-values. The agent balances investigating new choices with making use of the knowledge it has learned by employing an exploration-exploitation method (Richard S. Sutton and Andrew G. Barto, no date).
A discrete-event simulation framework called SimPy is used to carry out the simulation (SimPy Documentation, no date). Customers arrive at random times, go for a refrigerator, and are then assigned in accordance with the choices made by the Q-learning agent. Throughout time, the agent modifies its decision-making process by taking lessons from the results of its actions.

## Results
The simulation was performed using one to ten refrigerators, and each configuration was running ten times. For every setup, the average number of lost customers was noted.
The plot illustrates the results, which show that the average number of lost customers tends to decrease as the number of refrigerators grows. This implies that the Q-learning agent is successfully acquiring the ability to make choices that maximize client satisfaction within the specified context.
